Here are the five .NET 10 breaking changes you're hitting:

**1. `[InlineArray]` + explicit `StructLayout(Size=…)`**
.NET 10 throws `TypeLoadException` if you specify `Size` on an `[InlineArray]` struct. Remove the explicit size — the runtime computes it automatically.

```csharp
// Before (breaks in .NET 10)
[InlineArray(16)]
[StructLayout(LayoutKind.Explicit, Size = 64)]
struct MyBuffer { ... }

// After
[InlineArray(16)]
struct MyBuffer {
    private int _element0;
}
```

**2. `DriveInfo.DriveFormat` on Linux**
.NET 10 now returns the real filesystem type (e.g., `"ext4"`, `"tmpfs"`) instead of the previous (often incorrect) value. Update your string comparisons to match actual Linux filesystem names.

**3. NU1510 warnings — NuGet package pruning**
.NET 10 enables package pruning by default, trimming unused transitive references at restore time. If the warnings are noise, suppress with:

```xml
<PropertyGroup>
  <NuGetPrune>false</NuGetPrune>
</PropertyGroup>
```

Or resolve them by removing unnecessary `PackageReference` entries that are now auto-pruned.

**4. Transitive NuGet audit**
.NET 10 changes `NuGetAuditMode` default from `direct` to `all`, so transitive dependencies are now audited for known vulnerabilities. You'll see new `NU1903`/`NU1904` warnings. Fix by updating vulnerable transitive packages, or pin versions explicitly. Don't suppress these — they're security-relevant.

**5. `FilePatternMatch.Stem` is no longer nullable**
`Stem` changed from `string?` to `string` (returns `string.Empty` instead of `null`). Change null checks:

```csharp
// Before
if (match.Stem is null) { ... }

// After
if (match.Stem.Length == 0) { ... }
// or
if (match.Stem == string.Empty) { ... }
```
